🌐 Create First Record in Route 53
Step 1 — Create the Record

In the AWS Console, navigate to Route 53 → Hosted Zones
Click on your hosted zone: needtoknowEc2.com
Click Create Record
Enter record name: test(this creates test.needtoknowEc2.com)
Record type: A (default)
Value / Route traffic to: 11.26.36.213
Leave all remaining settings as default (TTL, routing policy, etc.)
Click Create Records
🖥️ Verify via CloudShell
Step 2 — Open CloudShell & Install bind-utils

Click the CloudShell icon in the AWS Console top navigation bar
Run the following to install DNS query tools:
  sudo yum install -y bind-utils
Step 3 — Verify with nslookup

Run:
  nslookup test.needtoknowEc2.com
✅ This confirms the A record resolves — it returns the IP 11.26.36.213
Step 4 — Deep-dive with dig

Run:
  dig test.needtoknowEc2.com
📋 This gives more detailed DNS information including:
ANSWER SECTION — the resolved IP address
TTL — Time To Live value
Query time — how long the lookup took
Authoritative nameserver — which NS server responded
💡 Tip:nslookup gives a quick confirmation, while dig is preferred for troubleshooting as it shows the full DNS resolution chain and metadata.
